glpR_K_D, bimodal distribution induced by G3P/Glycerol

2022-01-13 

"
-----------------   nomenclature

inactive promoter for glpD   inPD_R

  active promoter for glpD   actPD

inactive promoter for glpK   inPK_R

  active promoter for glpK   actPK

Gly                 Glycerol

============ promoter 

G3P + inPD_R → G3P + actPD + R      rp1= konD * G3P * inPD_R   (promoter activation) 

G3P + inPK_R → G3P + actPK + R      rp2= konK * G3P * inPK_R   (promoter activation) 

R + actPD → inPD_R                  rp3= koffD * R * actPD       (promoter deactivation) 

R + actPK → inPK_R                  rp4= koffK * R * actPK       (promoter deactivation) 


============ transcription

actPD → actPD + mD         rc1= ktrsc * actPD               (transcription by active promoter) 

actPK → actPK + mK         rc2= ktrsc * actPK               (transcription by active promoter) 

inPD_R → inPD_R + mD       rc3= ktrsc /10 * inPD_R      (r_a_i = 10, this is arbitrary)

inPK_R → inPK_R + mK       rc4= ktrsc /10 * inPK_R

PR --> PR + mR             rc5= ktrsc /15 * PR          (r_DK_R= 15, this is semi-arbitrary, it is higher than the above ratio, as Elisabeth has data showing R promoter activity is less than that of K or D even in glucose medium. The mbio 2015 paper also stated like what I do here.)

============= translation 

mD → D                rl1= ktrsl * mD               (translation of D)

mK → K                rl2= ktrsl * mK               (translation of K)

mR ->R                rl3= ktrsl * mR               (translation of R)

============== transportation (newly added) 

null -> G3P           rt1 = ktrsp_g3p * 50          (ideally GlpT should appear here. As it is not modeled, I assume a constant level 50 here. This allows the two transportation rates have the same unit.)

null -> Gly           rt2 = ktrsp_gly * K

============ feedback 

K + Gly → K + G3P              rf1= kpf * K * Gly     (positive feedback)
                                            
D + G3P  → D (+ DHAP)          rf2= knf * D * G3P     (negative feedback)

#### ignored ( DHAP → G3P  )

============ degradation 

mD → null              rd1= dmD * mD             (mRNA degradation)

mK → null              rd2= dmK * mK

mR -> null             rd3= dmR * mR

D → null              rd4= dpD * D            (protein degradation)

K → null              rd5= dpK * K

R -> null             rd6= dpR * R

============= 

bacteria volume = pi*(0.8/2)^2*3.0 = 1.51 micrometer^3 (rod shape)
number of gene copy  = 1, i.e. inPD_R + actPD = inPK_R + actPK = PR = 1

=============

I will play with 
1. konD/koffD and konK/koffK
2. trsp_g3p and trsp_gly
3. kpf and knf

I will assume the same degradation rate and translation rate, since no information of protein level is available.

"
params_glucose <- list(
  # promoter 
  konD= 0.1,
  koffD = 0.001,
  konK= 0.1,
  koffK = 0.001,
  # transcription
  ktrsc = 1,
  r_a_i = 10,
  r_DK_R = 15,
  # translation
  ktrsl = 0.5,
  # transportation
  ktrsp_g3p = 0,
  ktrsp_gly = 0,
  # feedback
  kpf = 0.1,
  knf = 10,
  # degradation
  dmD = 0.069,    # mRNA half life 10 min, log(2)/10
  dmK = 0.069,
  dmR = 0.069,    
  dpD = 0.023,
  dpK = 0.023,   
  dpR = 0.023,    # protein half life 30 min, log(2)/30
  # constants
  PR = 1,      # promotor for R 
  GlpT = 50    # T for G3P transportation
)

params_g3p_low <- params_glucose
params_g3p_high <- params_glucose
params_glycerol_low <- params_glucose
params_glycerol_high <- params_glucose


params_g3p_low$ktrsp_g3p <- 1
params_glycerol_low$ktrsp_gly <- 1

params_g3p_high$ktrsp_g3p <- 10
params_glycerol_high$ktrsp_gly <- 10
